This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) category as it deals with zero-shot learning in the context of fine-grained object recognition, retrieval, and image captioning. It also involves the use of visual prototypes and semantic spaces, which are common concepts in computer vision. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques such as learning projection functions and maximizing structural consistency, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category. 

The use of auxiliary semantic prototypes and the focus on bridging the gap between visual and semantic spaces could also place this paper in the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) category. 

The paper's emphasis on semantic prototypes and their incompleteness could also suggest that it belongs to the Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) category. 

Finally, the paper's focus on fine-grained object recognition and image captioning could also place it in the Multimedia (cs.MM) category.
